x1="3" x2="10" y1="21" y2="14"></line></svg></div></div></figure></div><p>这是<a href="https://fred.stlouisfed.org/series/DCOILWTICO">欧佩克生产的削减</a>！拜登绝对可以吹牛。</p><p>而且他还应该吹嘘自己如何<a href="https://news.yahoo.com/biden-offer-1-5-billion-222449405.html">借钱以关闭核电站</a>，以便他们可以重新开始运营：</p><blockquote><p>拜登政府有望为15亿美元贷款，以了解关闭的美国核反应堆的第一次重新启动，这是加强联邦政府对原子行业支持的最新迹象……融资是融资的，因为拜登政府优先维持国家的舰队来维持美国的舰队。核电站有助于实现其雄心勃勃的气候目标 - 包括在2035年到2035年将电网脱碳的计划。</p></blockquote><p>这里的共同主题是<em>美国人民的能量丰富</em>。</p><p>包括廉价的石油和核能以及廉价的太阳能和电池将吸引左派气候活动家作为背叛。但是那些激进主义者无论如何都不会认可拜登。毕竟，他们没有在2020年。 </p><div class="captioned-image-container"><figure><a class="image-link is-viewable-img image2" target="_blank" href="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F59e6421c-8dc9-407e-97fa-51395d8e4f2e_921x534.jpeg" data-component-name="Image2ToDOM"><div class="image2-inset"><picture><source type="image/webp" srcset="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_424,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F59e6421c-8dc9-407e-97fa-51395d8e4f2e_921x534.jpeg 424w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_848,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F59e6421c-8dc9-407e-97fa-51395d8e4f2e_921x534.jpeg 848w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1272,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F59e6421c-8dc9-407e-97fa-51395d8e4f2e_921x534.jpeg 1272w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F59e6421c-8dc9-407e-97fa-51395d8e4f2e_921x534.jpeg 1456w" sizes="100vw"><img src="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F59e6421c-8dc9-407e-97fa-51395d8e4f2e_921x534.jpeg" width="712" height="412.82084690553745" data-attrs="{&quot;src&quot;:&quot;https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/59e6421c-8dc9-407e-97fa-51395d8e4f2e_921x534.jpeg&quot;,&quot;srcNoWatermark&quot;:null,&quot;fullscreen&quot;:null,&quot;imageSize&quot;:null,&quot;height&quot;:534,&quot;width&quot;:921,&quot;resizeWidth&quot;:712,&quot;bytes&quot;:44248,&quot;alt&quot;:null,&quot;title&quot;:null,&quot;type&quot;:&quot;image/jpeg&quot;,&quot;href&quot;:null,&quot;belowTheFold&quot;:true,&quot;topImage&quot;:false,&quot;internalRedirect&quot;:null}" class="sizing-normal" alt="" srcset="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_424,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F59e6421c-8dc9-407e-97fa-51395d8e4f2e_921x534.jpeg 424w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_848,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F59e6421c-8dc9-407e-97fa-51395d8e4f2e_921x534.jpeg 848w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1272,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F59e6421c-8dc9-407e-97fa-51395d8e4f2e_921x534.jpeg 1272w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F59e6421c-8dc9-407e-97fa-51395d8e4f2e_921x534.jpeg 1456w" sizes="100vw" loading="lazy"></picture><div class="image-link-expand"><svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" width="16" height="16" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="#FFFFFF" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" class="lucide lucide-maximize2 "><polyline points="15 3 21 3 21 9"></polyline><polyline points="9 21 3 21 3 15"></polyline><line x1="21" x2="14" y1="3" y2="10"></line><line x1="3" x2="10" y1="21" y2="14"></line></svg></div></div></figure></div><p>同时，格雷塔·敦伯格（Greta Thunberg）和许多其他气候活动家似乎<a href="https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2023/dec/05/no-climate-justice-without-peace-gaza-becomes-flashpoint-for-climate-activists">正在前进</a>，而其他人则参与了诸如<a href="https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-68121654">在蒙娜丽莎（Mona Lisa）扔汤</a>之类的表演特技表演。 “剩下的气候”不是一群人，他们可以像拜登这样的自由主义者总统感到高兴或安抚，也不是大多数美国人都希望看到的群体。</p><p>换句话说，拜登应该忽略厄运，而要专注于阳光充沛，乐观的能量丰富信息。他的政策在该部门有很大帮助，他应该为他们荣誉。</p><p>拜登还应该对经济产生阳光，乐观的信息。</p><h4> Bidenomics成功了，所以请在该唱片上运行</h4><p>四十年前，罗纳德·里根（Ronald Reagan）在阳光明媚的经济乐观平台上竞选连任。这是他著名的“美国早晨”广告的代表，在该广告中，他夸大了通货膨胀下降和利率下降： </p><div id="youtube2-pUMqic2IcWA" class="youtube-wrap" data-attrs="{&quot;videoId&quot;:&quot;pUMqic2IcWA&quot;,&quot;startTime&quot;:null,&quot;endTime&quot;:null}" data-component-name="Youtube2ToDOM"><div class="youtube-inner"><iframe src="https://www.youtube-nocookie.com/embed/pUMqic2IcWA?rel=0&amp;autoplay=0&amp;showinfo=0&amp;enablejsapi=0" frameborder="0" loading="lazy" gesture="media" allow="autoplay; fullscreen" allowautoplay="true" allowfullscreen="true" width="728" height="409"></iframe></div></div><p>拜登还不能吹嘘下降利率。但是他可以吹嘘一种经济，从大多数方面来说<a href="https://www.noahpinion.blog/p/at-least-five-interesting-things-804">，这是</a>里根在1984年所享受的经济。</p><ul><li><p> 1984年，通货膨胀率<a href="https://fred.stlouisfed.org/series/CPIAUCSL">约为4.36％</a> 。在2023年， <a href="https://www.whitehouse.gov/cea/written-materials/2024/01/11/december-2023-cpi-report/#:~:text=Inflation%20as%20measured%20by%20the,more%20analysis%20of%20today's%20report).">它为3.4％</a> ，由于<a href="https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2024-01-25/us-median-rents-fall-for-eighth-month-on-boom-in-new-apartments?sref=R8NfLgwS">租金下降</a>而降低。</p></li><li><p> 1984年，<a href="https://fred.stlouisfed.org/series/UNRATE">失业率</a>为7.5％；在2023年，它不到一半，仅为3.6％。</p></li><li><p> 1984年，<a href="https://fred.stlouisfed.org/series/FEDFUNDS">利率</a>超过10％；截至今天，它们是5.33％。</p></li><li><p> 1984年，<a href="https://www.macrotrends.net/2526/sp-500-historical-annual-returns#google_vignette">标准普尔500指数仅返回</a>1.4％，在1983年17.3％之后。2023年，它返回了24.2％。</p></li></ul><p>客观上，2024年在美国早晨。</p><p>主观上，美国人开始认识到这一点。虽然还为时过早说选民感到乐观，但很明显， <a href="https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2024-01-19/us-consumer-sentiment-jumps-price-outlook-hits-three-year-low?sref=R8NfLgwS">过度的悲观情绪正在消失</a>：</p><blockquote><p>密歇根大学的消费者情感指数上升了9.1分，这是自2005年以来每月最大的预付款，至78.8…[T]他的乐观态度很广泛，在年龄，收入和政治隶属关系之间取得了进步。超过一半的家庭期望其收入至少与通货膨胀率一样快……消费者对当前财务状况的看法上升到了两年的高度，而对未来财务状况的期望攀升至2021年以来最高。</p></blockquote><p>附带说明，有趣的是，经过十年的高通货膨胀和两次衰退之后，经济情绪也在1983年初的垃圾场中。在1983年以来，里根（Reagan）举办了著名的广告时，盛行的乐观情绪巨大且持续的增长，这一乐观情绪： </p><div class="captioned-image-container"><figure><a class="image-link is-viewable-img image2" target="_blank" href="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F55721bde-cc9e-489b-920f-67f8e6d38609_1318x450.png" data-component-name="Image2ToDOM"><div class="image2-inset"><picture><source type="image/webp" srcset="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_424,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F55721bde-cc9e-489b-920f-67f8e6d38609_1318x450.png 424w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_848,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F55721bde-cc9e-489b-920f-67f8e6d38609_1318x450.png 848w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1272,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F55721bde-cc9e-489b-920f-67f8e6d38609_1318x450.png 1272w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F55721bde-cc9e-489b-920f-67f8e6d38609_1318x450.png 1456w" sizes="100vw"><img src="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F55721bde-cc9e-489b-920f-67f8e6d38609_1318x450.png" width="1318" height="450" data-attrs="{&quot;src&quot;:&quot;https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/55721bde-cc9e-489b-920f-67f8e6d38609_1318x450.png&quot;,&quot;srcNoWatermark&quot;:null,&quot;fullscreen&quot;:null,&quot;imageSize&quot;:null,&quot;height&quot;:450,&quot;width&quot;:1318,&quot;resizeWidth&quot;:null,&quot;bytes&quot;:58801,&quot;alt&quot;:null,&quot;title&quot;:null,&quot;type&quot;:&quot;image/png&quot;,&quot;href&quot;:null,&quot;belowTheFold&quot;:true,&quot;topImage&quot;:false,&quot;internalRedirect&quot;:null}" class="sizing-normal" alt="" srcset="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_424,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F55721bde-cc9e-489b-920f-67f8e6d38609_1318x450.png 424w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_848,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F55721bde-cc9e-489b-920f-67f8e6d38609_1318x450.png 848w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1272,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F55721bde-cc9e-489b-920f-67f8e6d38609_1318x450.png 1272w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F55721bde-cc9e-489b-920f-67f8e6d38609_1318x450.png 1456w" sizes="100vw" loading="lazy"></picture><div class="image-link-expand"><svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" width="16" height="16" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="#FFFFFF" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" class="lucide lucide-maximize2 "><polyline points="15 3 21 3 21 9"></polyline><polyline points="9 21 3 21 3 15"></polyline><line x1="21" x2="14" y1="3" y2="10"></line><line x1="3" x2="10" y1="21" y2="14"></line></svg></div></div></figure></div><p>无论如何，拜登在这里有很大的机会扮演里根的角色，并提醒人们经济是好的。当然，另一种选择是在卡特（Carter）的一部分中玩，并为可能已经过去的<a href="https://www.pbs.org/wgbh/americanexperience/features/carter-crisis/">“自信危机”感叹</a>。</p><p>当然，拜登自然希望像任何候选人一样为改进而获得信誉。他这样做有意义？基本上，拜登做了四件事，这些事情可能使经济成为非平凡的提升：</p><ol><li><p>他让杰罗姆·鲍威尔（Jerome Powell）担任美联储椅子，而不是任命一个可能允许通货膨胀率猖ramp的肮脏椅子。</p></li><li><p>他允许在公共土地上进行大量的石油钻探，并鼓励其他一些国家开始抽油。这有助于降低石油价格，在帮助限制通货膨胀的同时推动了实际经济。</p></li><li><p>他制定了主要的工业政策（《筹码法》和《 IRA》，导致了工厂建设和制造业雇用的繁荣。</p></li><li><p>他的财政赤字相当大，这可能已经抵消了较高利率的总需求，从而使实际经济保持健康。</p></li></ol><p>如果我拜登，我不会在这里吹牛，因为大多数人都害怕联邦预算赤字。但是其他三个很高兴谈论。</p><p>工厂的建设繁荣应尤其是自豪。用通货膨胀调整的术语，这是美国企业在很长一段时间内花在新工厂上的最多的。 </p><div class="captioned-image-container"><figure><a class="image-link is-viewable-img image2" target="_blank" href="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fb8191a25-9abe-4f2c-9111-a0475c9bc6a6_1318x450.png" data-component-name="Image2ToDOM"><div class="image2-inset"><picture><source type="image/webp" srcset="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_424,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fb8191a25-9abe-4f2c-9111-a0475c9bc6a6_1318x450.png 424w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_848,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fb8191a25-9abe-4f2c-9111-a0475c9bc6a6_1318x450.png 848w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1272,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fb8191a25-9abe-4f2c-9111-a0475c9bc6a6_1318x450.png 1272w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fb8191a25-9abe-4f2c-9111-a0475c9bc6a6_1318x450.png 1456w" sizes="100vw"><img src="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fb8191a25-9abe-4f2c-9111-a0475c9bc6a6_1318x450.png" width="1318" height="450" data-attrs="{&quot;src&quot;:&quot;https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/b8191a25-9abe-4f2c-9111-a0475c9bc6a6_1318x450.png&quot;,&quot;srcNoWatermark&quot;:null,&quot;fullscreen&quot;:null,&quot;imageSize&quot;:null,&quot;height&quot;:450,&quot;width&quot;:1318,&quot;resizeWidth&quot;:null,&quot;bytes&quot;:62840,&quot;alt&quot;:null,&quot;title&quot;:null,&quot;type&quot;:&quot;image/png&quot;,&quot;href&quot;:null,&quot;belowTheFold&quot;:true,&quot;topImage&quot;:false,&quot;internalRedirect&quot;:null}" class="sizing-normal" alt="" srcset="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_424,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fb8191a25-9abe-4f2c-9111-a0475c9bc6a6_1318x450.png 424w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_848,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fb8191a25-9abe-4f2c-9111-a0475c9bc6a6_1318x450.png 848w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1272,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fb8191a25-9abe-4f2c-9111-a0475c9bc6a6_1318x450.png 1272w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fb8191a25-9abe-4f2c-9111-a0475c9bc6a6_1318x450.png 1456w" sizes="100vw" loading="lazy"></picture><div class="image-link-expand"><svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" width="16" height="16" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="#FFFFFF" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" class="lucide lucide-maximize2 "><polyline points="15 3 21 3 21 9"></polyline><polyline points="9 21 3 21 3 15"></polyline><line x1="21" x2="14" y1="3" y2="10"></line><line x1="3" x2="10" y1="21" y2="14"></line></svg></div></div></figure></div><p>这一繁荣在很大程度上是<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/americas-factory-building-boom-93dfb8f5">《筹码法》和《 IRA》的结果</a>，这两者都在特定的战略技术（分别是半导体和电池）中进行了私营部门的投资。繁荣时期正在提供建筑工作，并且在工厂完成后的几年内，它将提供制造业的工作，最重要的是 - 大量的实际商品。</p><p>当前和未来的利益当然值得大喊。但是，也许更重要的是工厂建设繁荣的代表 - 它代表了一个<em>实际上完成工作的</em>管理。</p><p>如果您查看上面的图表，您会注意到特朗普下根本没有工厂的建设繁荣 - 实际上，支出实际下降了。尽管经济总体强劲。尽管事实是特朗普已经明确承诺将制造业返回美国海岸。尽管关税和大量大胆，但他从未设法在重新设置美国制造业方面取得任何实际进步。</p><p><em>但是拜登有</em>。拜登（Biden）对制造业的晋升比特朗普（Trump）更安静，但事实证明，他在轻声说话并拿着一把大棍子。特朗普谈论了一场关于重新搬迁工厂的大型游戏。拜登只是去了。</p><p>因此，如果我拜登，我的竞选信息可能会这样：经过多年的压力，美国人应该休息一下。他们没有被告知社会在崩溃，一切都太可怕了，我们只能通过选举一个吼叫的煽动者来解决它，而是应该对自己进行一些对待。他们应该获得便宜的电力，廉价的汽油和便宜的住房。他们应该得到工作，收入上升和<a href="https://www.noahpinion.blog/p/great-news-about-american-wealth">财富上升</a>。最后，至少要感谢拜登政府的政策，他们得到了应有的目标。</p><p>我不是政治专家，而不是远射。但是对我来说，这听起来像是一个非常自然的信息，可以继续运行。 </p><div><hr></div><p class="button-wrapper" data-attrs="{&quot;url&quot;:&quot;https://www.noahpinion.blog/subscribe?&quot;,&quot;text&quot;:&quot;Subscribe now&quot;,&quot;action&quot;:null,&quot;class&quot;:null}" data-component-name="ButtonCreateButton"><a class="button primary" href="https://www.noahpinion.blog/subscribe?"><span>现在订阅</span></a></p><p class="button-wrapper" data-attrs="{&quot;url&quot;:&quot;https://www.noahpinion.blog/p/biden-should-run-on-a-message-of?utm_source=substack&utm_medium=email&utm_content=share&action=share&quot;,&quot;text&quot;:&quot;Share&quot;,&quot;action&quot;:null,&quot;class&quot;:null}" data-component-name="ButtonCreateButton"> <a class="button primary" href="https://www.noahpinion.blog/p/biden-should-run-on-a-message-of?utm_source=substack&utm_medium=email&utm_content=share&action=share"><span>分享</span></a></p><p></p><p></p>; 
Interview: Sarah C. PaineA scholar of the 20th century explains the conflicts of the 21st. https://www.noahpinion.blog/p/interview-sarah-c-paine https://www.noahpinion.blog/p/interview-sarah-c-paineNoah Smith Tue, 30 Jan 2024 06:22:37 GMT <div class="captioned-image-container"><figure> <a class="image-link is-viewable-img image2" target="_blank" href="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F2cee21d2-04e5-4d7a-9931-293a574ebf89_598x594.jpeg" data-component-name="Image2ToDOM"><div class="image2-inset"><picture><source type="image/webp" srcset="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_424,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F2cee21d2-04e5-4d7a-9931-293a574ebf89_598x594.jpeg 424w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_848,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F2cee21d2-04e5-4d7a-9931-293a574ebf89_598x594.jpeg 848w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1272,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F2cee21d2-04e5-4d7a-9931-293a574ebf89_598x594.jpeg 1272w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F2cee21d2-04e5-4d7a-9931-293a574ebf89_598x594.jpeg 1456w" sizes="100vw"><img src="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F2cee21d2-04e5-4d7a-9931-293a574ebf89_598x594.jpeg" width="598" height="594" data-attrs="{&quot;src&quot;:&quot;https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/2cee21d2-04e5-4d7a-9931-293a574ebf89_598x594.jpeg&quot;,&quot;srcNoWatermark&quot;:null,&quot;fullscreen&quot;:null,&quot;imageSize&quot;:null,&quot;height&quot;:594,&quot;width&quot;:598,&quot;resizeWidth&quot;:null,&quot;bytes&quot;:18225,&quot;alt&quot;:null,&quot;title&quot;:null,&quot;type&quot;:&quot;image/jpeg&quot;,&quot;href&quot;:null,&quot;belowTheFold&quot;:false,&quot;topImage&quot;:true,&quot;internalRedirect&quot;:null}" class="sizing-normal" alt="" srcset="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_424,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F2cee21d2-04e5-4d7a-9931-293a574ebf89_598x594.jpeg 424w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_848,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F2cee21d2-04e5-4d7a-9931-293a574ebf89_598x594.jpeg 848w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1272,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F2cee21d2-04e5-4d7a-9931-293a574ebf89_598x594.jpeg 1272w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F2cee21d2-04e5-4d7a-9931-293a574ebf89_598x594.jpeg 1456w" sizes="100vw" fetchpriority="high"></picture></div></a> <polyline points="15 3 21 3 21 9"></polyline><polyline points="9 21 3 21 3 15"></polyline><line x1="21" x2="14" y1="3" y2="10"></line><line x1="3" x2="10" y1="21" y2="14"></line></figure></div><p>我第一次在与我的朋友Dwarkesh Patel进行的<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=YcVSgYz5SJ8">视频采访</a>中遇到了海军政策和军事历史学者<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sarah_C._Paine">Sarah CM“ Sally” Paine</a> 。她能够将当前事件和20世纪历史放置在一个具有凝聚力的框架中，并用简单又有用的语言解释该框架的能力立即感到震惊。在世界陷入<a href="https://www.noahpinion.blog/p/a-lot-of-what-you-see-in-the-news">新的冷战的</a>时候，热战的威胁<a href="https://www.noahpinion.blog/p/were-not-ready-for-the-big-one">迫在眉睫</a>，我们需要像潘恩这样的分析师，他们对我们的成功以及我们失败的地方有深刻的了解挑战。</p><p>因此，我接触了Paine，我们进行了漫长的电子邮件采访，您可以在下面阅读。除其他事项外，我们讨论了大国的类型，全球秩序的本质，中国轴心的崛起，习近平和普京的目标，美国内部和欧洲政治的挑战以及美国需要什么接下来。我发现她的论点非常有说服力，而且非常清醒。</p><p>潘恩目前是美国海军战争学院战略和政策系<a href="https://usnwc.edu/Faculty-and-Departments/Directory/Sarah-CM-Paine">教授</a>。她还是几本书的作者，包括<em><a href="https://www.amazon.com/Wars-Asia-1911-1949-S-Paine/dp/1107020697">亚洲战争，1911年至1949</a></em>年（我目前正在阅读）， <em><a href="https://www.amazon.com/Sino-Japanese-War-1894-1895-Perceptions-Primacy/dp/0521617456">1894  -  1895年的中日战争：感知，权力和首要地位</a></em>，以及<em><a href="https://www.amazon.com/Japanese-Empire-Strategy-Restoration-Pacific/dp/1107676169">日本帝国：大战略从明治恢复到太平洋战争</a></em>。</p><p>在这次采访中表达的想法是她一个人。</p><div><hr></div><p> <em>NS：我对您对“海事”与“大陆”权力的想法以及全球海事秩序的想法特别感兴趣。您能给我快速介绍这意味着什么吗？</em></p><p> SP：必要时，海上力量可以主要由海上捍卫自己，而大陆力量则不能。这与地理有关：像英国这样的岛屿力量只能通过越过大海来入侵，而法国也面向开阔海洋的法国也有一个长长的海岸，面向德国和低地国家。法国和德国都反复入侵该边界，因此要求军队捍卫它。无论他们是否购买大海军，由于这种土地脆弱性，它们的地理位置都是大陆。</p><p>从历史上看，欧亚大陆的伟大文明都是大陆帝国。海洋帝国后来来了。前者着重于扩展到连续领土，而后者则集中在贸易的扩张上。对于后者来说，该领​​土是继发贸易的第二个领土，它们采用了生产交易产品或作为贸易基础的领土。海上帝国（例如荷兰共和国）有兴趣维持一项通用国际法律制度，以便所有人都可以在安全方面进行交易。国际法的创始父亲雨果·格罗蒂斯（Hugo Grotius）是荷兰共和国的公民。大陆帝国的重点是将世界雕刻成影响领域，每个领域都是法律世界，并且经常努力以彼此的费用扩大。</p><p>工业革命通过产生复杂的增长来颠覆两种类型的帝国。已经专注于贸易的海洋帝国比大陆帝国在统治领土上的位置要适应这种变化的位置要好得多。此外，从革命法国和拿破仑战争开始，民族主义的出现逐渐在全球范围内传播，这使帝国的代价不可持续，因为占主导的人民抵制。海洋帝国最终发现，谈判共同的互动规则比持续敌对领土要多得多。</p><p>第二次世界大战后，基于规则的国际秩序起飞。在第一次世界大战稳定欧洲的明显失败之后，这场战争的应征者（其成年后已经花在了大萧条中，在第二次世界大战中都升任了战略领导地位。他们对世界大战和全球抑郁症的解决方案是在全球范围内建设机构，包括联合国，国际货币基金组织，北约和欧盟的前任机构（欧洲经济共同体）和世界贸易组织（关于一般性协定关税和贸易）。他们建立了强大的机构来创建论坛，以口头解决问题，而不是在军事上与之抗争。</p><p>这种新兴的全球秩序从根本上是海上的，因为海洋是世界上原始的全球网络，可以将所有人与所有事物联系起来。 2020年，国际海事安全中心的一篇文章建议，有66-70-80-90-99的规则强调，全球财富的66％来自或不远，全球70％是海洋，80％，80％它的人口是沿海地区，有90％的商品乘海上到达，而99％的数字交通则由潜艇电缆进行。 <a class="footnote-anchor" data-component-name="FootnoteAnchorToDOM" id="footnote-anchor-1" href="#footnote-1" target="_self">1</a>这反映了从土地到商业的电力货币的变化。即将到来的全球海事命令着重于通过最大程度地减少交易成本来使财富复杂化，而即将到来的竞争，破坏财富，大陆帝国的秩序着重于互相破坏。古老的系统破坏了财富，新的财富创造了它。</p><p> <em>NS：海上力量往往与大陆的行为不同？</em></p><p> SP：历史上地理迫使大陆大国筹集大型军队或被邻居吞噬。边境安全必须是政府的首要任务。这产生了一种倾向，将经济定向供应陆军和驻扎在家里的大型驻军倾向于在专制方向上影响政治机构。古代雅典的长墙将雅典变成了一个被土地牢不可挡的岛屿，而英国拥有一定程度的国家安全，大陆大国无法实现。这种比较安全使雅典和英国的政府和人民能够专注于通过贸易加剧财富。然后，这激励政府机构保护和促进贸易，鉴于大量利益相关者，人们倾向于民主。在其首都的高峰期都没有一支大型政变的常规军。两者都利用自己的财富为海军提供资金来保护他们的海洋通道和海上航线，并在海上防守。</p><p> <em>NS：当今海事秩序的关键要素是什么？</em></p><p> SP：按全球秩序，我的意思是国际法律规则，适用于州和非国家行为者，以及制定，修改和管理这些规则的机构。现有海事命令的关键要素是：每个国家决定是否加入的国际机构，条约和法律。这些机构并不是创建单一的霸权力量，而是反映了所有成员的贡献。他们只有在我们都同意支持和遵守它们的情况下才有效。机构和法律正在进行中，并且可能始终保留，以便随着条件的变化和后代的适应。</p><p> <em>NS：为什么海事权力少受军事政变和威权主义的影响？我当然可以想到军事独裁者接管海上权力的时代 -  1930年代日本的军国主义者，奥利弗·克伦威尔，印度尼西亚的苏哈托，甚至是公元前411年在雅典发生的政变，我们有数据表明海上力量不太容易发生对威权主义？</em></p><p> SP：我没有关于大陆或海上权力更容易受到政变的数据。我猜想，在首都拥有庞大且缺乏强大法律机构的国家庞大的国家拥有庞大的国家将更容易发生政变。自第二次世界大战以来，海上和大陆帝国都撤退了。没有海洋帝国，只有中国和俄罗斯等大陆帝国。自第二次世界大战以来，由大陆和海洋缘政治地位的国家组成的基于海洋规则的秩序，基于战后机构的实力：联合国，Gatt（现为WTO），欧洲人群体（现为欧盟），世界银行，世界银行等等。在遵守规则的范围内，他们遭受的政变较少。根据定义，政变是继承规则的细分。</p><p> <em>NS：此外，跟进您对第二次世界大战后的命令的评价：如果基于海上贸易的规则命令为世界带来了更大的繁荣，并为海上权力带来了更大的力量，为什么我们现在看到专制大陆的复兴像中国，俄罗斯和伊朗这样的权力？</em></p><p> SP：独裁者与独裁者主导的人口有益于什么。根据定义，独裁者想垄断政治权力。习近平，弗拉德米尔·普京（Vladmir Putin）和其他独裁者的主要目标是继续执政，以不改善人民的繁荣。的确，要继续执政，他们将需要束缚公民的野心，他们自然会寻求政治权力至少与他们对民族繁荣的经济贡献相称。习近平不同意，并且一直在逮捕他最成功的企业家 - 他不想替代权力基础。</p><p>随着苏联在1991年的爆炸，中欧人民可以选择的很少见：东方或西方。由于西方比俄罗斯提供的繁荣和自由更大的繁荣和自由，他们选择了西方。在几十年中，俄罗斯人将重点集中在其国家，这使中欧人能够建立自己的国内机构，以在俄罗斯返回试图统治他们时生存下来。随着他们越来越多地按照国际法和法律规则扮演，他们的生活水平迅速上升。同样，邓小平领导下的中国专注于内部发展。现在，中国回来了，试图统治邻国。由于这个原因和其他原因，它的增长率迅速下降。</p><p>悲剧是，独裁者寻求无法实现的目标，这些目标最终通过抑制经济增长和可能引发战争来破坏自己的公民。独裁者充其量会抑制国内的增长，以控制自己的人口，并在最坏的情况下迅速摧毁财富，而战争以统治邻居。</p><p> <em>NS：让我们谈谈一些因素，导致美国及其在第一次冷战期间和之后施加的基于规则的命令的下降。</em></p><p><em>美国通过入侵伊拉克损害了基于规则的命令，从而鼓励俄罗斯等国家（可能）中国发起自己的侵略性战争？</em></p><p> SP：问题有两个部分：首先，美国通过入侵伊拉克损害了基于规则的命令多少？我不知道如何量化这样的答案。基于规则的命令是生存的，因为国家的优势遵循了它。布什的高级人员加强了海湾I的世界秩序，涉及击退伊拉克对科威特的入侵。他通过与支持和资助战争的盟友进行仔细的共识来做到这一点。尽管许多亲密的盟友对伊拉克的首选战争，他的儿子通过单方面采取行动在首选战争中采取单方面行动损害了世界秩序。多少伤害？谁知道。然后，他的战争被证明很难退出，数十年来吞噬了稀缺的资源。</p><p>的确，美国通过旷日持久的大规模部署在遥远的地方造成了破坏，到剧院，这些剧院被多个专制国家包围，目的是阻止他们附近的民主进一步发展。他们是布什少年计划的否决球员。民主的目标是不可行的。浪费伊拉克资源而不是在家中可行目标中的资源的机会成本很高，就像我们在痛苦和扩大的社会分裂中所看到的那样。在家中明智的投资比国外昂贵的管道更可取。</p><p>该问题的第二部分涉及伊拉克战争是否鼓励俄罗斯和中国发起自己的首选战争。在这个问题中嵌入的是美国的假设，即其他国家的行动是美国所做或不做的事情的函数。美国人以自己对自己的自我重要性的假设来倾诉自己。俄罗斯和中国是统治者打算继续终身权力的统治者的大陆帝国。普京和第十一专注于领土和个人权力的扩展 - 目标与美国行动无关。在入侵他人之前的计算中，美国的弱点比美国侵略更具兴趣。两者都接受侵略作为其首选国际制度的规范，即他们寻求推翻基于规则的系统的对立面。普京因其2008年的Russo-Georgian战争或2014年对乌克兰的入侵而受到西方罚款。这对他的计算要比伊拉克的战争更为重要。同样，乌克兰战争的结果将引起中国的兴趣，因为它计算了国际对台湾袭击的反应。</p><p> <em>NS：美国内部政治两极分化和经济功能障碍有多少重要？</em></p><p> SP：很多。西方著名的二十世纪历史学家阿诺德·托恩比（Arnold Toynbee）写道：“文明死于自杀，而不是谋杀。”共和党正在自杀及其自杀威胁我们所有人。多方制度和对不同意见的尊重构成了民主的基础。当只有一种意见是可以接受的，而另一些人要么被暴力大喊或威胁到独裁统治时，当最少愿意按照规则决定对其他所有人的最卑鄙的人时，这就是独裁统治。</p><p>如此众多共和党代表不愿证明2020年选举（顺便说一句选举）是违反他们誓言维护《宪法》的誓言。那些失去选举的人必须接受损失。这就是民主的运作方式。努力下一次合法地赢得胜利。说实话，按照规则扮演，对他人进行文明的对待也是共和党声称拥护的家庭价值观的基础。</p><p>民主国家在很大程度上超过了全球战争和和平时期经济增长的独裁统治，这在很大程度上是因为他们的公民能够通过争论，反驳和反驳与彼此的不同思想互动，而不是基于不幸的单词选择而不是基于愚蠢的，而是基于基于不幸的单词选择与可用证据的经过深思熟虑的参与，以支持一个人的观点，并随着新证据的使用而改变自己的观点。重新评估不是一个缺陷，而是美德。正如普京和XI每天插图​​的那样，独裁者倾向于对不良决定并消除批评家的批评者，首先关注最准确的批评者。</p><p>如果唐纳德·特朗普（Donald Trump）被允许推翻2020年大选，那么今天将没有乌克兰，俄罗斯军队将在波兰的边界上，西方将处于捍卫自己的位置要弱得多。共和党需要重返保护美国国家安全和民主的核心价值。如果这是不可能的，因为囚犯接管了庇护所，那么那些专注于捍卫我们的国家安全和民主的人需要组成另一个政党。也许像过去的辉格党一样，共和党也在开展课程。</p><p>为了解决美国，美国人需要互相倾听，互相容纳，互相妥协，投票并接受选票的结果。</p><p> <em>NS：让我们谈谈俄罗斯和中国。您认为俄罗斯实际上威胁着欧洲多少？如果乌克兰跌倒，巴罗的海是接下来的？波兰怎么样？如果乌克兰在2022年迅速倒塌，这个答案会有所不同吗？</em></p><p> SP：俄罗斯威胁欧洲，因为其领导人的目标是重现苏联帝国，而不能与民主共存。相反，民主国家对独裁者构成生存威胁。如果民主党领导人赢得自由选举，为什么独裁者不能呢？答：显然他们的公民不支持他们。独裁者的解决方案：分别为俄罗斯和中国的最近民主国家 - 乌克兰或台湾。几十年来，欧洲试图通过购买俄罗斯的能源并欢迎其黑暗的钱来打球，但无论如何入侵。</p><p>没有针对俄罗斯的非军事解决方案。如果乌克兰跌倒，摩尔多瓦和波罗的海国家将接下来，然后来波兰。同时，俄罗斯将继续其激进的信息战，以激发西方的社会分裂。俄罗斯利用社交媒体鼓励西方公民互相打开和邻居，而不是真正的罪魁祸首，这些罪魁祸首是构成实际生存威胁的独裁者。</p><p>如果乌克兰在2022年倒闭，那么西方的局势将是可怕的。中国本来会看一个落入俄罗斯的国家。为什么不去台湾呢？其他国家，由于他们的许多领土不满，可能会想到，为什么不这样做呢？然后，基于规则的命令使我们能够以称为信用卡的塑料件来环游全球，并允许弱者和强大的人期望他们的合同能够履行合同 - 全球订单本来将要出路。这最终将使我们所有人陷入困境。独裁者将巨大的财富和权力带给自己，而不是给公民，更不用说给邻居了。</p><p>对于俄罗斯来说，乌克兰只是菜单项，即开胃菜，然后再吃一顿饭。餐点已经结束的不是甜点。如果乌克兰占上风并清理了足够多的国内腐败以符合欧盟（EU）会员资格的步伐，它将引起一个问题：为什么俄罗斯也不能清理其腐败呢？为什么那些居住在莫斯科和圣彼得堡两个特权城市以外的俄罗斯人不能像欧洲人一样生活？为什么它最受欢迎的反对派领导人以武器级毒素为目标，被枪杀或停在监狱中，以判处长期判决？为什么俄罗斯人必须过19世纪的香蕉 - 公共生活？答案是：专政。这就是独裁者下的人的生活。金正恩的朝鲜是经过几代复杂的贫困之后结束的方式。</p><p>对于独裁者而言，民主国家固有地威胁着这两者，因为公正的选举排除了独裁者，而独裁者的寄生性质意味着独裁统治的生活标准随着时间的流逝而逐渐下降。独裁者为他们的公民的劳动提供了努力，以在国内投射增长力量，并在国外摧毁财富的权力。民主国家对领土扩张不感兴趣，而对经济增长不感兴趣。独裁政权不能让他们一个人呆着，因为他们将民主国家的高生活标准视为对自己的起诉和致命威胁。因此，民主国家必须捍卫自己。对于普京或XI等独裁者来说，没有足够的住宿。</p><p>西方需要落后于乌克兰，并规范军事和经济援助，并为俄罗斯和中国挑战筹集财富赚钱的全球秩序的决定（这是使中国富裕的命令）的决定提供的长期努力。与开放闸门开放独裁扩张相比，支持乌克兰的支持很便宜。</p><p> <em>NS：至于中国，他们有多少领土野心超出了台湾的征服？</em></p><p> SP：中国宣称整个印度省，南中国大部分地区，并在东南亚河流系统的源头堵住了。中国的野心超出了全球秩序本身。腰带倡议是全球的。这不是要赚钱，而是要扩大影响力。中国想要的不仅仅是邻近领土和合规的邻居，还希望拥有具有中国特征的世界秩序。仅供参考：民主不是中国的特征。这是台湾人的特征，中国希望出于与普京打击乌克兰的同样原因而淘汰。</p><p>西方通过坚持在一起，在国内加剧了经济增长，并为共产党辅助自杀策略赢得了最后的冷战。没有市场定价共产主义制度，由于缺乏准确的估值而严重破坏了资本和劳动力。西方致力于加剧这些经济负担。普京和第十一缺乏共产主义曾经并且属于反西方主义的强大意识形态。随着以前的殖民世界与他们更加紧密地合作，他们将有机会将以前殖民的西方的罪恶与目前殖民的东方的罪恶进行比较。他们会发现，中小型国家只能在数量上找到安全，而这些数字是通过不断发展的基于规则的国际秩序的规则以及支撑它的国际和地区机构的规则。</p><p> <em>NS：我认为，由于美国政治部门和中国压倒性的权力的结合，乌克兰不能指望美国成为其坚定的朋友和支持者，而如果乌克兰将要有，欧洲必须加紧长期保证主权和安全。您认为这基本上是正确的吗？欧洲现在不做更多帮助乌克兰的最大原因是什么？</em></p><p> SP：中国的力量并不是帮助乌克兰的障碍；相反，它为乌克兰当务之急提供了帮助，以免西方未能团结起来对欧洲的安全威胁，鼓励中国在亚洲发动一场地区战争，而其他较小的权力则遵循自己的区域不满。</p><p>我不是欧洲众多和多样化国家复杂的国内政治专家。我可以谈谈一些美国人（怀疑者）没有看到更多做更多的原因的原因。其中一些原因可能也适用于欧洲：</p><p> （1）怀疑者认为他们的个人繁荣并不取决于世界事件。然而，交付我们所有与我们联系的贸易和信息的船只和电缆取决于导航的自由，这取决于世界秩序维护导航和共享信息的自由。世界秩序是基于主权的：大大不能摄取小规则的规则。如果我们生活在和平中，那么交付商品和信息的交易成本是最小的，而财富的化合物则是最小的。现在，俄罗斯和中国正在与国际体系交战，交易成本正在上升。由于这些原因，经济增长将与刚刚结束的冷战期的高增长率不符。倾向于俄罗斯和中国的领土食欲不会保留该系统，而只会加速其衰落。我们的繁荣确实取决于世界活动，因此我们更好地关注和对齐钱包。</p><p> (2) Opportunities in wartime are ephemeral, proving the adage that an ounce of prevention is worth a pound of cure. Either provide aid at the right time or the price tag soars. The doubters do not anticipate that if Russia wins this one and China wins the next one, it will be far more difficult to protect their physical let alone economic security. They cannot imagine a seismic change of the international system. Yet World War I took down the monarchies of Russia, Germany, and Austro-Hungary and put fascism and communism on steroids. Think of Greece&#39;s ruined Parthenon that stands in mute testimony to a world order destroyed.</p><p> (3) The doubters have become jaded by the US wars in Iraq and Afghanistan where local partners were unable to do the fighting. Ukrainians, by contrast, are doing the fighting and fighting well. The doubters are probably unaware of “the principle of continuity” in warfare, derived from Carl von Clausewitz&#39;s classic, <em>On War.</em> Ukrainians have massively degraded Russia&#39;s military at the cost of pennies on the dollar for the West. Give Russia a breathing space and it will reconstitute its forces to return for an even deadlier land grab as it did after its initial landgrab in 2014. So, keep the pressure on—follow the principle of continuity. Give Russia no breathing space. This is a proxy war for the West but not for Russia, which has already lost more military personnel than in its bankrupting, decade-long war in Afghanistan.</p><p> The value of victory is existential for Ukrainians and Putin, but not for the Russian people. Ukraine poses no threat to their existence. Leverage this asymmetry in the value of the object to keep Ukraine in the fight. The Russian army has a history of breaking: it broke in the Russo-Japanese War (1904-5) when the value of the object was far greater for the Japanese and Tsar Nicholas II than for the Russian people. It broke again in World War I for a lack of competent generalship and adequate supplies (sound familiar?). It survived World War II only through massive US Lend-Lease aid, an effort that China is not about to duplicate. Meanwhile, as Russia throws ever more resources into Ukraine, it cannot protect its long borders elsewhere. And this may ultimately constitute a genuine national security threat to Russia not the dystopian fairytale about supposed Ukrainian Nazis.</p><p> (4) The doubters, like all of us, prefer good news to bad news. But the bad news is real: Russia is going to be a problem for the long term. For the situation to change requires Russian leaders to change their minds, a highly unlikely event for a very long time. When Putin dies or is overthrown, there will be a destabilizing leadership struggle. Succession is an inherent weakness of dictatorships. After Joseph Stalin suddenly died, Soviet leaders immediately called off the Korean War in order to focus on their internal power struggle with each other. It then took years for the narrowing list of contenders to consolidate power. No one can predict when Putin&#39;s last day on the job will be.</p><p> (5) Finally the opportunists wish to use the war in Ukraine against domestic opponents. Apparently some Republican Party members prefer a Ukraine loss to portray as a Joe Biden loss in the upcoming presidential elections. Imagine if US politicians had done this in World War II to undermine Franklin D. Roosevelt. Then it took the attack on Pearl Harbor to quell the isolationists who incorrectly thought that war could not come to them. Europeans should understand better than Americans the costs of allowing big countries to run roughshod over small ones. Europe became the battleground of two world wars for a failure to face problems sooner rather than later. Europeans are cognizant of the threat. They are working together. But it takes time for 27 European Union (EU) members and 31 NATO members to come to agreement. When they do, their agreement is powerful.</p><p> A Ukrainian victory could come through the collapse of the Russian army or Putin&#39;s inevitable succession, but both could take time. In the meantime, keep the aid flowing and the sanctions tightening so that the compounded effects of the economic growth that fails to occur in Russia puts Russians on track for a North Korean existence. Those who undermine the rules-based order get a global time out—no equal participation until the destructive behavior ceases. If the problem cannot be solved, this is how to manage it—gradually widen the gap in living standards between the free and unfree worlds. This is how the last Cold War was won.</p><p> <em>NS: Another question. You&#39;ve talked about how in great-power conflicts, the side with the most and best allies typically prevails. Currently, China — the world&#39;s largest manufacturer by far, and second-most-populous nation — is in a de facto alliance with Russia, Iran, and North Korea. Is that a dominant coalition? If not, what US-led coalition could conceivably overmatch it?</em></p><p> SP: No this is not the dominant coalition. China plus failing states Russia, North Korea, and Iran is not a winning team. Much of the population is starving in North Korea. Iran is a theocracy—a medieval form of government following medieval practices—like killing over clothing. Even China is now engaged in wealth stifling policies under Xi Jinping.  Moreover, China is an awful ally. It does not believe in the equality of states, rather that China should dominate any “allies.” Prime allies are not North Korea, but South Korea, Japan, Australia, New Zealand, Canada, and all of Europe (minus Belarus and several others of little economic consequence). The global rules-based order enshrined in international organizations and treaties is the winning system.</p><p> China became an economic powerhouse when it rejoined this maritime trading order and played by the rules of international law. It is now back to its historic paradigm of China at the center and all others must kowtow to the emperor in Beijing. Western investors are fleeing, sanctions are multiplying, its internal housing/loan bubble is imploding, its most talented entrepreneurs are imprisoned, its internal repression is growing, while genocide against its Muslims continues. Manufacturing moved into China over the last thirty years when China played by the rules, and now it is moving out as China jettisons the rules. India, Vietnam, Mexico and many other countries are more than happy to help fill the gap.</p><p> Currently, Russian and Chinese brutality are propelling their weaker neighbors to cooperate with each other and to seek out strong friends. The most powerful alliances are based on existential threats—the type that Russia and China are now posing.</p><p> <em>NS: Let&#39;s follow up on the idea of what happens if China and Russia prevail in their respective neighborhoods — Russia conquering Ukraine and perhaps dominating Eastern Europe, and China conquering Taiwan and dominating East Asia. Can you spell out explicitly how American prosperity suffers in that scenario? And would there be any direct security threat to America?</em></p><p> SP: Russian conquest of Ukraine and Chinese ingestion of Taiwan would mark the beginning not the end of the feast on other people&#39;s territory. Both Russia and China envision an authoritarian world order, dividing the world into massive spheres of influence—spheres yet to be created. Small- to mid-sized countries (ie most countries) beware. They will lose their equal sovereign rights under the present rules-based world order in which the rules apply to the weak and strong alike. Instead we will all regress to the ancient world in which the strong do what they can while the weak suffer what they must. There will be no recourse to international law or institutions, just to the psychopathic emperors entrenched in Russia and China. An authoritarian world order at best will stifle economic growth and creativity, and at worst it will usher in a succession of wars as intended victims resist these plans.</p><p> In the United States, both China and Russia have already begun the cyber war, by targeting the government, universities, corporations, journalists, professors, and citizens with cyber theft. Both countries target their own citizens in the United States to silence them and sometimes to blackmail, kidnap, poison, or kill them. If their territorial aggrandizement proceeds, the areas of the globe subject to their authoritarian model will grow along with the menu of targeted individuals that will increasingly include US citizens who dare criticize either.</p><p> Since the 2010 US Supreme Court Citizens United ruling, allowing the wealthy—including foreign governments—to make unlimited anonymous contributions to US political campaigns, we have no idea which of our public representatives are beholden to dark money from foreign dictators. We also do not know how many of our public representatives have been honey trapped by Russia, which is famous not only for the defenestration of former Putin supporters, but also for taking intimate photographs to blackmail victims—in this case presumably to cast desired votes. We should have a hot line for the latter to break such foreign influence that endangers us all.</p><p> Prosperity, ours along with that of others, depends on minimizing the costs of our many business transactions with each other. Regulating these transactions is the origin of international law. If we play by the rules, the credit cards work, we can plan, partners cannot renege on contracts, the pricing is market based, etc. As Russia and China expand, leveling one country at a time, the amount of wealth destroyed will be massive, as Ukraine illustrates, while any war-ravaged territory taken will not be capable of generating wealth for decades. China&#39;s and Russia&#39;s plans are negative sum—there will be less aggregate global wealth for every territory they take and this will ruin their victims and ultimately impoverish us all as it shrinks the area where the rules still apply.</p><p> When the last Cold War ended, Russia and China ceased funding insurgencies, the civil wars died down, and the world achieved unprecedent growth, benefiting the rich and poor alike. Americans are shocked that these comparatively peaceful and prosperous years are over. The transaction costs are rising because Russia and China no longer intend to play by the rules. This is the long-term threat to our economic prosperity and national security.</p><p> The immediate security threat for the United States is that the authoritarians may win through the ballot box with the election of Donald Trump, an admirer of Putin and other authoritarian leaders. Trump will fast-track this authoritarian dystopia.</p><p> <em>NS: Also, regarding our list of allies, the US has been drawing a lot closer to India, which is the most populous country in the world, a rival of China, and a potential platform for manufacturing investment. Do you see that partnership developing into some sort of alliance?</em></p><p> SP: India is allergic to the idea of alliances. It was one of the founders of the non-aligned movement. Expect that to continue. Throughout the Cold War, India had very friendly and productive relations with Russia, but strained relations with the United States. US segregation appalled Indian leaders, who understood full well that segregation applied to them. For good reason, they were also bitter about Western colonialism generally. Nevertheless, Chinese aggression is propelling India to cooperate with the United States, which now has an increasing number of citizens of Indian origin who can bridge communications between their native and adopted countries.</p><p> Alliances and partnerships are more a function of common enemies and the lethality of the threat than of shared values. The Grand Alliance of World War II included the British Empire, the United States bent on eliminating empires, and the Soviet Union bent on eliminating capitalists. Yet the three shared a common, lethal primary enemy in Hitler and the alliance survived precisely until Hitler&#39;s death, when the unifying shared common enemy was no more. Arguably China is the primary adversary of both India and the United States and this forms the basis for security cooperation. Should the threat become lethal to both (not just one), expect the cooperation to deepen.</p><p> <em>NS: And following up on my question about Europe, do you think Europe is doing enough to hold up its end of the NATO bargain, in terms of spending the necessary money and producing the necessary armaments to help Ukraine and other East European states resist Russian力量？ If not, how can we get them to step up more?</em></p><p> SP: I am not an expert on the many countries of Europe, so I cannot explain their domestic impediments to expeditious funding for Ukraine. Both the United States and Europe have been slow to ramp up miliary production. But this takes time. In World War II, the United States funded a two-ocean navy only in 1940 and those ships did not arrive in theater until 1943 at a time when the United States had a massive manufacturing base that it no longer possesses. Ukraine of course is gearing up production as fast as it can, particularly of drones. To take back territory, Ukraine must own the skies over its troops otherwise Russia will slaughter them. Conversely if Ukraine owns the skies, the tables will turn and Russian troop morale will be unlikely to hold—they have no compelling personal reasons to fight to take Ukrainian territory while Ukrainians have existential reasons for fighting to regain and protect their own territory.</p><p> There are two ways for Ukraine to retrieve territory: shatter the morale of the Russian army, in which case the mine fields will not matter, or shatter Putin&#39;s domestic monopoly of power through the protraction of the war beyond the patience of his followers. Stalin wound up dead behind a bedroom door that no one opened until they were sure he must be dead. The sycophants were sick of the purges. The ensuing succession cat fight meant an instant end to the Korean War that had long stalemated. As Putin runs out of lieutenants to blame for his miscalculations, perhaps the survivors will tire of the defenestrations.</p><p> Leaders in all democracies need to explain to voters the lethality of the threat, the impossibility of compromise, and the cost-effectiveness of aid to Ukraine given the stakes. Putin and Xi have “unlimited objectives” meaning they intend to overthrow the international rules-based order, not simply to reform it (a limited objective). Compromise with adversaries pursuing unlimited objectives is called appeasement because the compromise positions them to return for the kill. For decades the West tried to compromise in its strategy of “transformation through trade” tried in the 1990s up through the completion of Nord Stream II. Russian invasions simply gathered force: Georgia 2008, Ukraine 2014, and Ukraine 2022. Compromise takes two. Putin and Xi have made clear their ambitions. Either we organize with our partners to defend ourselves or the dictators will continue picking us off one by one.</p><p> <em>NS: Let&#39;s talk about how much military strength the US really has. I have been <a href="https://www.noahpinion.blog/p/people-are-realizing-that-the-arsenal">banging the drum about this</a> , but it feels like no one is listening, and it feels like people in the defense, Congressional, and foreign policy establishment are complacent. The US has no civilian shipbuilding industry to speak of, and our Navy is getting massively outproduced by China in terms of number of ships and submarines per year. Our munitions production has struggled to reach one-tenth of what it was in the mid-1990s, and I can&#39;t imagine our drone and missile production is much better. It seems like in any protracted conventional war, China will be able to outproduce us, the way we outproduced the Axis powers in World War 2. Is this an accurate assessment, in your view? Are people in the establishment sufficiently concerned about this? And if the answer to both of those questions is &quot;yes&quot;, what is being done to remedy the situation, and what more can be done?</em></p><p> SP: These are all excellent questions that I cannot answer because these are not areas of my expertise. You need to interview someone with expertise on production, production timelines, logistics, bottlenecks to production, etc. You also need to interview someone with expertise on the combined industrial capacities of the United States and all of its likely allies. Wars over the nature of the international system are global and involve alliances.</p><p> Here are some points to consider: In World War II, it took the United States several years to gear up production. The United States never fought on the main front of World War II, which was the Russian front in Europe and the China front in Asia. I define the main front to be where the Axis and Allies (Russia) deployed the preponderance of their forces. Unlike in World War I when Russia fell for lack of arms and food, the United States through Lend-Lease supplied both the Russians and British. It is crazy to let a partner&#39;s army go down for lack of supplies—Ukraine&#39;s current predicament if Congress does not get going.</p><p> Japan in World War II had a productive capacity only a fraction of that of the United States, but managed to give the United States a real run for its money even as Japan conducted campaigns throughout China. In other words, those with comparatively small industrial bases can wreak havoc. Like China today but unlike the United States then or now, Japan lacked many of the key resources for war, most notably oil (and also food), which was ultimately the ruin of Japan. Without energy, armies, ships, and planes cannot move far.</p><p> The Axis lost World War II for a combination of many reasons—not just a single reason such as production. These reasons included their own overextension of trying to gobble up and hold more than was possible, gobbling in the most alienating way imaginable, and, in so doing, transforming failing states (famine- and purge-ridden Russia and disintegrating China) into lethal adversaries 。 Russia has just transformed Ukraine into a lethal adversary and supercharged European defense cooperation. If China reduces Taiwan to rubble, expect the same transformation in Asia. China&#39;s unprovoked threats have already spurred unprecedented, and until recently politically impossible, Japanese and Korean security cooperation. If China continues its menacing approach to foreign policy, it will wind up with two additional nuclear neighbors.</p><p> Wars turn on many instruments of national power, not just the military. In global wars, the side with the most effective alliance system typically wins. The side that most effectively leverages diplomacy to share and coordinate resources and campaigns does better over time—daily we see the diplomacy in action as allies step in to provide incremental aid to Ukraine while US politicians try to hash out an aid/border deal. In the world wars, the theaters of conflict were not only land campaigns, but blockades to throw enemies back on their own dwindling resources, finance, propaganda, government-private sector production coordination, etc. There was a major civilian component concerning production, home-front support, and, most importantly, on strategy: how to coordinate these resources and when and how to deploy them. World War II also turned out well for the West due to all the wartime planning for post-war reconstruction and institution building, planning that requires careful civil and military input and coordination—planning that was totally absent in the War in Iraq,</p><p> We are at a pivotal moment in our country&#39;s history. Will our leaders do their job, which is above all to protect our national security or will they continue with their scorched-earth strategies against each other that leave our governmental institutions hamstrung? It is time for the articulate among them to speak to Americans, as Franklin Delano Roosevelt did in the Great Depression, to explain the stakes, the choices, the trade-offs and the consequences and back up their recommendations with evidence. Roosevelt did not dumb down his radio talks about impending bank holidays, but detailed the issues and supported his recommendations with evidence. Voters were far less well educated then than they are now. Not only politicians but journalists need to quit the unsupported ad hominem attacks on each other and instead lay out the trade-offs to be made and the rationale for them.</p><p> <em>NS Thanks. Final set of questions. Looking out at the US media and opinion landscape, what are the key things that you think Americans don&#39;t yet understand about the current geopolitical situation, that they most need to understand?</em></p><p> SP: Americans most need to understand:</p><p> 1. <em>The connection between their personal well-being with a rules-based order at home and abroad.</em> The most efficient and least violent way to run transactions between individuals and states is through laws. The alternative is wealth destroying armed chaos. Russia&#39;s approach to Syria and Ukraine illustrates what happens when there are no rules: the places where Russia intervenes become smoking ruins. What it loots goes to its tiny governing elite, which lacks the wealth to replace the wreckage it leaves behind.</p><p> 2. <em>The difference between posturing and governing</em> . Making the headlines by creatively insulting one&#39;s political opponents does not solve problems; rather it derails solutions by deepening political divisions. Governing entails engaging both the argument and the counterargument, considering the best evidence supporting both, and then compromising to produce legislation that reflects not a minority but the diversity and complexity that is America. As columnist Mark Shields observed, “Politics is additive.”</p><p> 3. <em>A win-win strategy is much more likely to succeed than a winner-take-all approach</em> . Reduce the debt, not by defunding the IRS but by collecting the taxes that are legally due. Before Russia escalates to a Baltic invasion and points westward, arm the Ukrainians. Make a border deal to staunch the flow of illegals, who are illegal and should abide by US law by entering legally.</p><p> 4. <em>The difference between opinion and evidenced-based conclusions</em> . Solving US problems requires data to inform decision making. “News” reporting has gravitated toward opinion and prediction, rather than the collection of information about events, decisions, and research findings—the necessary data for others (not the reporter) to form conclusions to guide choices.</p><p> 5. <em>The imperative to get beyond “crotch” politics</em> . Too many Americans obsess over limiting bathroom access, personal pronoun use, rare cases of transgender amateur sports participation, and intervening in other people&#39;s health care. As they fiddle these tunes, the world around them burns: If Ukraine loses, the international order will crumble; if Americans on the bottom two-thirds of the social pyramid consider their economic prospects stymied, social unrest will grow; if illegal immigration is ignored, divisions between border- and non-border states will widen; if climate change is not addressed, costs of climate disasters will mount; if the United States fails to hold free and fair elections and if losers refuse to accept defeat, democracy will not survive in the United States. The Declaration of Independence laid out the core US values of life, liberty, and the pursuit of happiness. Democracy is the basis for all three.</p><p> <em>NS: And can you talk about what specific actors can do here to improve the situation? What can people in the technology industry do, business-wise or politically, in order to support the needed changes? How about the DC establishment, the media, or just normal everyday Americans?</em></p><p> SP: Don&#39;t re-elect let alone donate to Trump or those who declined to certify the 2020 election. They failed their most important official responsibility: to honor their oath of office to uphold the US Constitution. Without the rule of law, democracy is dead. If we do not follow the laws, then what? Our whims? The local crime boss? How can those who considered themselves fairly elected have refused to certify the election results for the same ballot that elected them? Don&#39;t like the results? Attract more voters in the next election. Don&#39;t like the laws? Amend them. Kicking over the chessboard is not the answer.</p><p> Both private companies and public servants should think about border security and supply chain security together. Failing states on US borders threaten US security. Consider a multi-decade, incremental effort to encourage investments in Central America that would profit US businesses, create livelihoods there, bring supply chains closer to home, and, in so doing,  gradually staunch the flow migrants—in a win-win strategy.</p><p> Create a free on-line media pool limited to highly informative daily articles—not predictions about the future or moral judgments about the present, but fact-driven reporting. It should cover Congressional legislation, Supreme Court decisions, the voting records of legislators, the resumes of candidates, important research findings, and, lest we play half-court tennis and ignore the other side of the net, follow political and economic developments across the地球。 The Associated Press got its start during the Mexican-American War, when New York City newspapers “pooled” their resources so they could afford to cover the war. Make the internet work for voters instead of the trolls. Currently we are operating in an information vacuum left by the demise of local newspapers, the print press in general, and TV news viewership. Younger generations no longer rely on them.</p><p> For Americans generally, some neglected platitudes: Be kind to each other. Encourage others not to be mean. When others say something nice about someone, let that person know. Thank those who should be thanked. Try to forgive the little things and focus on the big things. For those who are senior, look out for those who are junior. For young and old: do not be afraid to change your mind. Reassessment is a virtue not a fault. Intransigence in the face of opposing evidence is a harbinger of senility.</p><p> For those concerned about American greatness, consider its origin. Was it leadership by the rudest and crudest people in the room? Decisions based on gut feeling rather than a careful examination of the available evidence? My-way-or-the-highway, scorched-earth politics? Or was it the capacity to think beyond the next election or annual report to the next generation? To think big. To act with optimism and faith in others. American greatness used to be based on innovation, top-notch experts in all fields, personal liberty not to tell others what to do but to make one&#39;s own choices, honesty and integrity as core values, a commitment to service, and to quote the Republican Party&#39;s greatest leader, “malice toward none with charity for all.”</p><p> The greatest generation of Americans were not the veterans of World War II who raised the Vietnam generation, but their parents, the veterans of World War I and the Great Depression, who applied can-do optimism and thought big to solve big problems. Despite the intense partisanship of the McCarthy era, in a few short years the Truman administration was instrumental in creating the Marshall Plan, the International Monetary Fund, the General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade, the United Nations, the North Atlantic Treaty Organization, the National Security Council, the Central Intelligence Agency, the Joint Chiefs of Staff, and the US Air Force, programs and institutions that fostered unprecedent global economic growth, allied cooperation, and US grand strategy, and held the peace in the West for three generations until Putin decided to overturn the global chessboard to impose on us his dystopian continental world of landgrabs, torture, murder, looting, and wanton destruction.</p><p> Now it is our watch. Time to plan, legislate, and act. </p><div><hr></div><p class="button-wrapper" data-attrs="{&quot;url&quot;:&quot;https://www.noahpinion.blog/subscribe?&quot;,&quot;text&quot;:&quot;Subscribe now&quot;,&qu